	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    the Contract</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:summerwynd@wanderersoftherealm.org">Mindelynn Spiritwalker</a> | 
		            12/12/2001 11:13:25 AM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">	The sinews of my muscles tighten as I lean forward. Ears straining to hear the discussion.  The flustered coloration of the woman, darkening with the vehemence she spits the words forth.  The set of the jaw of the man as he adamantly clings to his argument.  And I sit upon my rock, watching.  Soon a decision will be reached, and I will shimmy up the tree behind me, back to the solace of my room.  That lifeless room, in Kelethin that has of late become my prison.  How  I wish I had been born human, they did not have the idealistic beliefs of the Feir dal.  That one marriage could change generations of hate, death, and murder.  Sacrificing the happiness of one to appease the masses.  The Teir dal were liars and thieves, murders that would sooner slit my gullet than to love me.  Before me, the woman&#8217;s shoulders sag. The man steps forward and clutches her shoulders, resting his head against her back.  Their pain intermingling, sobs reaching my hiding spot.<BR>
	With a twist of my torso, I leap to the massive trunk behind me.  Muscles straining and darting for the soft glow of my bedroom window.  Staving off tears, they will fall soon enough.  She had fought for me, wanting me to know love before marriage.  Reminding my father of the love they had felt and the vows they swore on that day.  Yet, she had lost.  I saw the sag, the spirit waver, the thoughts darting to right and wrong.  But they were wrong&#8230;this was wrong.  Love is not forged in paper, it&#8217;s forged in fire, sweat and tears:  not parchment and meetings.<BR>
	Lithely I swung into the window and onto my bed, slamming my head into  my pillow with the force of a broken heart.  For yes, it was broken&#8230;never to know true love.  I would be wed to a foul smelling, ill-tempered,  cold and callous man.  Would I even last my wedding night before a blade finds my heart.  I lie in wait&#8230;for the steps outside my door, bringing the decision to my ears.  Having to sit and see the hurt and pain, and not being able to halt or alleviate it.  A tentative knock at the door, sends my heart racing.  The door creaks softly open, and the whisper of my name reaches my ears.<BR>
	&quot;Mindelynn?&quot; whispers my dearest friend, Summerwynd.  She&#8217;s heard my sobs, and I see the concern in my eyes.  Not pity, but the want to see me smile.  I had found this barbarian wandering about the woods of Kelethin, lost and ridiculed.  Aeldwan had warned me of the dangers of Northmen, that they had fierce tempers and cold eyes.  But my friend, nay she was neither of these&#8230;a soft spoken woman, who loved everyone without rancor.<BR>
	Sighing heavily, I lean up and place my hand beside me, encouraging her to join me. &quot; The Decision has been reached.&quot;  The perplexity in her eyes tells me that she&#8217;s not been informed of the plans my family have been negotiating. &quot; I am to marry,&quot; trying to swallow around that word, &quot;a teir dal.  That is what they were discussing this eve.&quot;<BR>
	&quot;You were eavesdropping?&quot; the look of shock was almost amusing.  Nay, Summer would never have done such a thing, it was too underhanded.  Placing my hand upon hers, and feeling the warmth there, reminding me of the fire of my tears.  <BR>
	&quot;Yes, it is my future they discuss.  Seems I am to marry over a contract&#8230;mother fought, but the logic seems clear.  To keep the forces of the Emperor at bay, I am to wed one of those cave dwellers.&quot;  The gravity of what I was saying, cutting my heart more and more with each word.  Almost spitting the words cave dweller, a thought crosses my mind.  What if I were not here for them to get, they would have to choose another.  I would be free.<BR>
	Searching Summer&#8217;s eyes, seeing the love there, I knew what I was to ask was cruel.  Never truly knowing her own family, I would have her sacrifice the one she found in mine, so that I could escape.  No, I couldn&#8217;t do it.  Looking away, my heart rails against me for cowardice.	A hand upon my shoulder, and the breath upon my ear&#8230;Summer&#8217;s eyes searching out mine.<BR>
	&quot;Dear sister, ask it&#8230;and it shall be done.&quot;  A tear escape&#8217;s her eyes.  She knows&#8230;she knows what I wish to ask her.<BR>
	Choking on the words and tears I try to hide. &quot;Can you help me?  I do not wish to marry this man, I do not wish to at all.&quot;  The sting of the tears &#8230;unhindered.  I crush my head to her shoulder, shuddering as the sobs wrack my body.<BR>
	Gently she tugs my chin, raising my face so that she can watch my eyes.  Quietly, wiping away the tears.  &quot;Sister, tis time to pack, shed the tears later.&quot; <BR>
	And with those words, she rises from the bed and walks to the dresser.  The scraping of wood against wood sends my thoughts crashing about me.  Quietly, stacking the clothes beside me on the bed.  Hiding her eyes, so I can not see what she is thinking or feeling&#8230;or whether she sheds a tear at my leaving.  Soon all my traveling gear is assembled on the bed&#8230;and then we hear them.  The footsteps, slowly scraping against the wood outside our rooms.  My mind reeling, Summer turns  to me and kisses my cheek.  Then I can only remember the limbs and bark beneath my fingers.  How had I gotten outside the window?  Where was Summer?<BR>
	The last few feet were beneath me, dropping, my fingers cling to the lush carpet of the forest floor.  Few sounds reach my ears, but I feel the outrage of my parents.  Screaming and venting their frustrations upon my friend, I wish to run and protect her.  Yet, my heart reminds me that Summer is a Northman, she can take care of herself.  And I would truly hate to be on the other end of her wrath.  Silent as a field mouse, I dart for the mountains.   There is a ship there that will set out soon, and I had every intention of being on that boat.  A few days travel brings me to the harbor, only to see the back of the boat as it sails away.<BR>
	Starving, I see an Kaoda dal man quietly watching me.  As I approach, he begins his sells spill&#8230;hair of Siren, pods of pure Mountain water to cure any ail. Sighing I see he lacks any food. Purchasing a fishing pole, I wander off to find a quiet spot upon the docks.  My thoughts reeling of all that is happening, I pull fish after fish in with the mechanical movements of a clockwork.  Walking within a dream of my own making, I find a spot behind the fire to cook my dinner, and wait for the return of another ship.  A kind gnome, who&#8217;s name slips me was nice enough to let me take a spot of his stone floor.  <BR>
	Upon waking, I hear the wailing of a boat on the rise, I quickly gather my gear, and leave a bit of coin on the desk for the man&#8217;s kindness.  The boat was of moderate size, and I was able to find solace below decks at the bar.  Though I was raised never to imbibe spirits, my mind needed a release from my thoughts.  As I brought the bitter fluid to my lips,  someone jostles my arm.  The glass shattering at my feet, turning I see a dwarf, a glowing hammer nestled into the crook of his arm.  Sighing, I notice the man was only trying to get a drink. As the bartender looks the other way, I gingerly lift a bottle of ale from behind the counter.  Grabbing the dwarf&#8217;s arm, I pull him along with me.  His eyes seem to search about as though guilty of some action, and seeing that he&#8217;s has committed no crime.  Spying the bottle, he licks his lips and reaches for the it.  Finding a quiet corner to pass the time, we share the bottle of ale and talk.  He&#8217;s a cleric of Brell in search of the undead that have infested the Common lands.   Telling of a place called Befallen, I see the gleam in his eye of bringing the demise of such creatures.  He tells of the evil of Teir Dal, and how they thrive on the dark arts of Necromancy.  Telling how the only good dark elf, is a dead one.  My mind tries to understand his anger, it&#8217;s there, hidden behind the mask of propriety.  There is more to this hatred that he has spoke of&#8230;a personal grudge.<BR>
	The knocking of wood upon wood, drags me from my drunken stupor with my new friend.  Stepping out on the deck, I see Freeport beginning to fall behind me&#8230;seems I missed our docking.  I leap into the water and swimming for shore, praying no sharks decides that Feir dal flesh in more appealing then fish.  Soaking wet, I drag myself ashore, and begin to remove my armor to dry in the warm sun.  Resting in my tunic and breeches, I quietly contemplate the adventure I have placed myself upon.  Lying back, I stare up at the sun, and think about my sister and the family I have left behind.  Would I ever see any of them again?  The heat of the sun upon my skin, my eyes grow heavy.  Soon between the alcohol and the excitement, I slip into unconsciousness.  My head slowly slipping to the sand, and the warmth of the sun covering me as if it were a blanket.<BR>
	The darkness of sleep surrounds me. There stands Summer, resolute and stubborn, a red hand print upon her cheek.  The eyes, hurt but refusing to show the tears that demand to be seen.  My mother and father, calling her names, gesturing to the door.  Yet, I feel that within my mother is glee, a silent happiness that she will not let my father see.  I had runaway, I had taken the choice from her.  She would not have to sell her daughter into a bondage that she herself would even refuse to imagine.  Yes, a bit of pride, that would be within her heart.  Summer packing her things and waiting on the docks&#8230;but she wouldn&#8217;t be alone.  Our friends would watch after her.  Aeldwan has taken a bit of a fancy to her, and would want to make sure she is safe.  Jakkee, my dear cousin, the three of them had become a family of sorts.  Yes, they would be together.<BR>
	The salty taste of lips upon mine, brought reality crashing back to me.  Eyes flying wide, a teir dal leaning over me.  His eye lids closed as his lips meet mine.  Shoving with the hatred of the ages, I push this man away.  Blinking slightly, his mind seems to come back to him.  The coldness dancing in his eyes, at my shock and disgust, My reaction amused him.<BR>
	Fastidiously, he stands and brushes the sand from his robe.  Glancing down at me, he states, &quot; what&#8230;does a kiss not wake the sleeping princess?  Though, sleeping such like, you only ask for the beggars to take your armor, silly child.&quot;  With the flick of his wrist and a dance of his eyes, he disappears.<BR>
	The bile rising in my throat at the thought of his lips on mine.  I stagger to my armor, and begin donning it.  The sun has slipped behind a cloud, and the wind coming off the harbor was beginning to chill my bones&#8230;or was it that kiss.  How dare he take such a liberty&#8230;who was he?  Spattering&#8217;s of conversations drifted down to me below the dock, seems there have been troubles in Freeport again.  My ears catch that the militia, of this harbor town, are not to be trusted.  Grabbing the last of my belongings, I venture into town to see what it would hold for me.<BR>
	Freeport is a town of dust, and cut-throats.  I try to find a room in North Freeport, among the knights and noblemen of the town, but to no avail.  The funds I have in the bank are low, and I can not find a room to rest my weary bones.  So I continue on, through the common lands.  Sometimes fighting my way against the Death fist orcs of the lands, but pushing on trying to find only a place to rest my head.  I come upon an empty  building, unknown of the dangers of the land, I pray to Tunare that the bed does not crawl with a life of it&#8217;s own.  Once more resting my head upon the hay, I feel eyes upon me. <BR>
	Dreams come to me of swirling mists, and dark incantations.  Of a barbarian man standing on a cliff with only a kilt against the storm on the horizon.  A force pushes him forward, falling from the cliff,  I see his legs are tied with a length of rope.  Plunging into the cold water. Laughter and mumblings of conversation.  The poor barbarian is pulled from the drink, a figure that appears behind him.  The tint of the skin glowing in the lightening of the storm, black hair whipping about his face.  It was the one that kissed me; I feel it within my bones.  The white of his teeth, gleam in the night with a sick twisted smile.  Turning, it&#8217;s as if he sees me&#8230;locking our eyes together.  Gently caressing the barbarian&#8217;s shoulder, as a lover might he, he pushes the man once more into the freezing water below.  With a flick of the robe, he&#8217;s gone from sight.<BR>
	I can feel the sweat upon my body.  Chilling me deep within my bones, almost touching my soul.  The silence of the wood lands about me, sends me leaping to my feet, was danger near?  A bear glances up as I leave the hovel I called home for a night&#8230;unconcerned with my passing.  I continue my trek towards the forest of Kithikore.  I must cross before the day passes.  For the dead walk Norrath once more in that wood.  They have name and reason, and it&#8217;s the destruction of all living things.  I did not wish to be on that menu.  Passing into the edge of the forest, I run&#8230;I run as though the servants of Innoruuk were after me.  As if Cazic thule saw my existence and wished to strike it down&#8230;.I ran like the wind, unnoticed and unseen.  Diving into a cave as the filtering light through the trees begins to wan,  hiding.  Ducking further and further into the cave, I bump into a small man.  I would call him a mix between a gnome and a dwarf, but I fear this would insult him.  <BR>
	&quot;Greetings Beautiful,&quot; he says.  A toothy smile greets my eyes, and a playful twinkle in his eyes. &quot; I&#8217;m Giggan, of Rivervale&#8230;Baker extradanaire&#8230;and lover of the great Kithikore.&quot;  And with a wink I seemed to make a new friend.  A halfling of such playfulness, I feel that I can rest easy once more.  Giggling, I get lost in the playful banter of my newfound friend.  He tells of the lands of Norrath, and how he will soon be able to spread his love of woman far and wide.  Blushing, I can see the life I wish to live&#8230;one of carefree once more.<BR>
	That night, Giggan offered his bed to me, and grabing a blanket and bounces off to the other room.  A man of wit and morals, I will be safe now.  Snuggling into a pillow, the headyness of the earth pervading my nose&#8230;and I feel the safety of Kelethin about me once more.  Then the dreams come.  There he was&#8230;  I knew it was him, I recognized the curve of his shoulders, as they were hunched over the table.  Diligently working on some concoction, boiling and bubbling.    The sulfur burning my nose, even though I knew I was only dreaming.  <BR>
	&quot;ah&#8230;my pretty, you have returned again.&quot;  A soft chuckle, he knows I am here.  Glancing left then right, I see if there is a portal out of this hell&#8230; yet, my eyes can not penetrate the darkness.  Turning I see those piercing beautiful eyes, as he saunters towards me.  Gingerly sitting on the edge of the bed, his fingers caressing my cheek, delicately pulling the tendrils of hair away from my face.  The skin burning where is hand  touchs, as though made of fire.  My eyes travel to the jar in his hands, and I can feel his eyes upon my lips.  His stare as tangible as the hand that scorched my cheek.  <BR>
	Mist swirling in the jar, coalescing and contracting.  My eyes are draw to an image locked within that jar.  As I strain to see more, I feel his breath across my cheek, his lips tentatively drawing to mine.  The scream comes deep from within me, past my heart, past my soul, past anything that I felt ever comprised my spirit.  I scream, one to scatter glass, and drive away the demons.  With a swirl of mist and magic, the dream scatters, as though it were made of glass.  Dissipating, as I try to regain my senses and my sanity.  Shaking my head, harder and harder, trying to rid my mind of that image.  Nay, it would not go, forever to cling to my soul.  That beautiful face, the visage of the barbarian I saw on the cliff the night before&#8230;locked in a mask and twisted mockery of life.  Trapped in that swirling mist, screaming and beating against the jar.  Those horror stricken eyes searching mine, pleading for me to help, to release him from his confines.  Nay, I would never forget that face, or the horror I saw there.<BR>
	A hand about my shoulders, lifts me from the last clinging remnants of my dream .  Lying on a bed, too small for my frame, and the caring arms about my frame.  The tears came, unbridled and unbidden.  They poured from my eyes, as the waterfall of Stonebrunt pours into the river.  All powerful,and yet never ending.  I cried, for my parents, my friends, and the sister I had left behind.  Soothing hands upon my hair, the kisses upon my cheek, and the love that poured from my newfound friend.  He wished to take the pain, the insanity that awaited me when I slept. <BR>
	Kissing the top of my head, &quot; dear Mindelynn, all is well, rest please&#8230;no more screaming&#8230;no more tears.&quot; Fingertips brushing my cheeks, &quot; you sully your beauty with such tears.&quot;  And the press of his lips to my head, how sweet this man was, to care for the insane.  Moving quickly, Giggan places my head upon his chest, and pets my hair&#8230;trying to coax me once more to rest.  Oblivion claims me once more, I was thankful that Tunare robbed me of my dreams the rest of the night.<BR>
	Upon waking, I notice that Giggan has gone.  A note informs me he&#8217;s in the gorge; his friend had been possessed by an Evil eye.  The creature was using his friend to waylay and steal from passerby&#8217;s, caring not for his welfare or free thought.  Giggan had gone to save him, and I would journey to help them.  Finding my way to the gorge was easy enough, but I must avoid the Minotaurs that patrolled the passageways.  Gently fading into the surrounding, I scurry along the edge, until I see a break in the gorge.  A Minotaur in front of me begins sniffing the air, as though it smell my presence.  Watching the dawning realization that it&#8217;s quarry was near, his eyes become level to my own.  Bolting for the safety of the plains, I pray that I can outrun and confuse this great beast.  Claws across my back tell me that my legs will fall short on this journey.  Rolling to the left, I bring my sword across his belly.    Splicing his armor just a hair, I feel the stink of its breath upon me.  The smell of rotted meat pervading my nostrils.  Its shadow fall&#8217;s across me, the beast is twice my size. Leaping to the right, I twirl the blade about once more.  Catching the beast across the ribs, his left arm swings out swiftly knocking me to the ground, senseless for a moment.  Thoughts and actions reeling, a hoof connects with my ribs, and I double from the pain. I reach into my boot to pull forth a dagger, stabbing for the beast&#8217;s lower calf. Blindside by hoof to the head, sends me reeling one more. Vision clouded from the dust of the battle and the blood seeping into my eyes.<BR>
	A flash of light, almost blinding my eyes, and the life siphons from the minotaur in front of me.  Eyes glassy with surprise and loss of life, the beast never saw the touch that had killed him.  A shuffling of dirt, my eyes shift to a shadow against the walls of the gorge.  I can not see him, but I know he is there.  I know it to be male for a woman would have spoken by now, if only to make clear that I should thank them for saving my life.  Yet, my silent savior tries to remain that.  Feeling along the walls of the gorge, I can hear him shift, and move.  Silent to my eyes; but not my senses.   <BR>
	&quot;The steps you take now will only enable me to track you better sir&#8230;so better show thy self.&quot; I state with more assurity than I feel.  Why did this man hide from my eyes?  He&#8217;s done nothing wrong&#8230;why hide?<BR>
	From the shadows stepped a creature I have never laid eyes on before.  My first instinct was to scream, run and hide, for fear he would destroy me with his massive fists.  Yet a gentle hand reaches out to me, brushing a lock of hair from my face.  I had heard rumors of Ogres, but never laid eyes upon one.  And here one stood, and had even saved my life.  Though his face was not the smoothness of an elven gentleman, I felt a closeness to this man.  Under my intense scrutiny, I see a slight tinge of red begin about his cheeks and spread to his ears.  Seems I was not the one feeling exposed here, turning for a moment, he returns to the shadows.  My eyes turn to he is hiding.<BR>
	&quot;thank you Great knight, for saving my life.&quot;<BR>
	&quot;You are new to these lands?&quot;   A question that I strained to hear, for it was whispered to me.  Did I frighten him?<BR>
	&quot;Yes, handsome&#8230;I&#8217;m new here.  And seems I have been fortunate enough to be saved by such gallantries.  You are truly a kind man.&quot;  I could almost sense the blush that burned his cheeks, hotter than most flames.<BR>
	&quot;Um, I am travelling to Oasis.  Perhaps we could talk more there?&quot; he asks.  The expectation and holding of his breath.  Was I also holding my breath?<BR>
	&quot;yes sir, I would like that.&quot;<BR>
	Emptiness grew about me, and I knew I was alone once more in the gorge..  A kind ogre, not the kind of creature that would break unsuspecting feir dal and boil their bones for broth?  Or was he a different from other ogres?  Aye, something was different about him.  Perhaps it was just the narrow escape that was making me contemplate his motives. He had been passing by when he heard the clash of battle.  What had been his name, had he told me?  Gathering my thoughts about me like a shield, I rushed to find Giggan.<BR>
	He was standing over a bulbous lump, the glazed iris staring past my ear.  The life leaked from beneath it, feeding the plains.  My stomach churned at the sight  of the fallen evil eye, and then my anger.  Eyes focusing on the fallen figure next to Giggan, were we too late?  Rushing to the figure&#8217;s side, I raise the man&#8217;s head, resting it upon my lap.  Naierly was coughing blood, and I felt the bond of magic within me grow.  Summoning my prayers, I place my hand upon his wound, the power rushing through my fingertips and into the wound.  Glowing tendrils of blue light intertwine in the flesh beneath my hand, rebuilding muscles and tissue.  A moan escapes his lips, kissing his forehead,  I say, &quot; all will be better soon.&quot;<BR>
	Giggan and I carry Naierly back to Giggan&#8217;s cottage in Rivervale. The safest place we could nurse him back to health for the cats grow hungry on the pains and there is little food to go around.  No Minotaurs plagued our trip on the way home, the clay caked walls seem to grow with even the thought of such beasts.  The journey seeming longer.  Upon return to the cottage, I chase Giggan out to get some food and supplies.  Placing Naierly on the bed, I lose myself in cleaning his wounds, and nursing him back to health.  Exhausting myself to the task, so when sleep comes I will not have the strength to dream.  Day turns to night, and then to day once more: and my limbs grow weary.  Gingerly tucking the blanket about Naierly and listening to his soft snoring, I join Giggan in the adjoining room. Knees buckling, I quickly lie down so that he can not see the exhaustion&#8230;yet I feel that he can sense it.  Then I am falling, into the darkness of unconsciousness.  <BR>
	Tap, tap<BR>
	Tap, tap<BR>
	What was that noise, the slight sound of metal against metal. Tap, tap.  Trying to ignore it, I quest for sleep once more. Tap, tap.  What could Giggan be working on this late?  Raising my head, I go to ask Giggan to please stave his hand till morning.  First the scent of sulphur strikes my nose as if it were a blow to the head.  I am no longer in Giggan&#8217;s home.  I have slipped into this man&#8217;s world once more.  And then I hear the whimpering, slight and almost inaudible.  Yet, I can hear the rising fear, and can almost feel the shivering within those sounds.  Eyes searching, they fall upon a man strapped to a table.  His eyes wide with fear and amazement.  The Teir dal&#8217;s back is to me, but the tapping is coming from his worktable beside his victim.  He raises his hand, and a tool floats to him, his raven hair moving in the wind about him&#8230;a spell.  He turns, though I still can&#8217;t see his face, arrogantly approaching his victim.  Caressing his cheek, the delicacy of a lover&#8217;s touch, bringing forth his other hand. A small metal contraption that he inserts into the ear of the man.  Some would say a scream is but the raising of one&#8217;s voice in a vocal manner that is inaudible of words, but nothing more.  Nay, that&#8217;s not what I heard from this man.  A scream, similar in feeling as that of the barbarian&#8230;and as I watch&#8230;the eyes go lifeless.  The teir dal reaches for the straps and with a flick of the wrist his victim is free.  The perversion of life then turned, placing both feet upon the floor&#8230;and stood.  Lifeless eyes turning to me, lurching towards me.  Hot breath upon my ear, tells me that it&#8217;s master has moved.  Fingers biting into my arms and the heat of his whispers on my ear.  He is behind me, I can feel his body heat against me.<BR>
	&quot;Do you like it dear?  I made it just for you,&quot; he says. &quot;Come Yipper, show my love what you can do.&quot;<BR>
	The creature, turning at the sound of his master, stood lifeless&#8230;waiting.  As the teir dal clapped his hands, the creature begins gyrating in a perversion of dancing.  It was not that the creature was dead, but that his will was gone, rendering him a slave.  Looking away, I realize I would never escape this torment.  But what more could he do to me?  <BR>
	Summoning strength I did not feel, I stated. &quot;And with that note, I shall be leaving sir.&quot; Turning, search for a way out.  Again those hands biting into my arms, the heat of him behind me. Heart racing, I panic, thrusting my head back into his mouth.  My heart dancing with glee when I hear the ummmphh from behind me.  My feet seem to know better than I an escape, for soon they were propelling me down a hallway.  Seeing a door ahead, I lunge for it.  Looking over my shoulder, I see him sauntering down the hall&#8230;slow and deliberate.  His creature of servitude at his shoulder, lurching down the hall in time with his steps.  Twisting the knob, I push through the door, and into eternity. The ground disappearing into a sheer cliff beneath my feet. Screaming, I cling to the knob for my life, and his laughter reaches my ears.  Floating  lithely in the air, his breath against my ear once more.<BR>
	&quot;There is no escape from me, my love.  You are mine, &quot; he glowers at me.<BR>
	Lurching forward, sweating, I am once more on the floor of the cottage.  Clutching at my head, wanting to rid the image of that man from my mind&#8230;yet he lingers still, behind my waking eye.  The whistle of a tea-kettle rouses me from my thoughts, and I see Giggan and Naierly staring at me.  Had I screamed again?  They must think me a lunatic.  Pressing a cup into my hand Giggan begins to rub my shoulders. His fingers finding the knots that have built up since the night I left my home&#8230;and the tears come once more.  Was I weak, could I not control my emotions?  Yet, I sob on, tears and shudders wracking my body.  Crying for a spirit that will not know escape.  Why was he tormenting me?<BR>
	Wishing not to burden my friend anymore, I left that day for the desert.  Wishing to see the kind Ogre again, I journey to the oasis&#8230;perhaps he was there.  Cresting a dune, I see him, sitting patiently&#8230;quietly, watching the sun set.  Steathily as a cat, I slipp beside him, and sit down.  A sigh of contentment escaping his lips, his eyes almost tearing from the beauty before us.<BR>
	&quot;Why did you save me?&quot; I ask, watching him jump a mile.<BR>
	&quot; Oogrr not know he not alone,&quot; he says and looks about for me.  Uncloaking from what little foliage, I search his eyes.<BR>
	He looks away, and begins to play with the sand.  Grabbing handfuls and tossing it into the slight breeze.  &quot;You needed help.&quot;  A statement&#8230;not an explanation.<BR>
	&quot;Yes, and you could have let me die&#8230;and then boiled my bones.&quot;<BR>
	&quot;Oogrr don&#8217;t do dat.  He not like elf meat.&quot;  Again staring at the sky and not me.<BR>
	&quot; Then WHY?&quot; The vehemence of the question surprising even me.<BR>
	&quot;We have a similar friend, someone who tol&#8217; me bout you&#8230;you know her too.&quot; Again a handful of sand into the wind.  He would not meet my eyes.<BR>
	&quot;Hmm&#8230;I never met an ogre before, so I guess you could be mistaken.  Well, If you wish, I can pay you for your assistance, &quot;I state, reaching for my coin purse.  A large, but gentle hand stays me.<BR>
	&quot;Summer was worried about you, she&#8217;s the one that speak of you.  Seems she&#8217;s our same friend.&quot;  Saying this, he removes his hand from mine as though it was uncomfortable.<BR>
	Quizzically, I ask. &quot;Why do you not like to touch me?  Is there something wrong with me?&quot;<BR>
	Uncomfortably, he answers. &quot;I ugly to your kind&#8230;you no like me much, I can see this.&quot; He turns to meet my eyes, and I see the pain. I see the beauty within those eyes, the kindness and strength.<BR>
	Standing, I look him almost in the eye. &quot;I see, you think since I am who I am, and you are what you are&#8230;then I don&#8217;t like you&#8230;well sir&#8230;your WRONG.&quot;  Almost spitting the word, how dare someone tell me who I like and don&#8217;t like.  And obvious my sister saw some good in him, for she would never make friends with cold or cruel person.  Nay&#8230;this was a good man, he just happened to be an ogre too.  Without a second thought, I wrap my arms about his neck and kiss his cheek. &quot;It&#8217;s the beauty on the inside I want to see sir, I don&#8217;t care what you look like.  So let us start anew, you as Oogrr, and I as Mindelynn.&quot;<BR>
	A gentle hand against my back, and the slight pressure of me against him.  I giggle, he&#8217;s hugging me, and is afraid to hurt me.  Yes, a sweet and kind man, indeed.  Staring into his sad eyes, intense pain against the back of my head, my head bouncing off his chest. Falling to the sand, my mind reels.  What happened?  I roll onto my back to see what has struck me, when what was left of an orc falls beside me.  I scurry away from it, it&#8217;s head turned at an odd angle.  Eyes unstaring, blood pooling in the sand as it leaks from his mouth.  Bouncing into an unmoving wall, I look up.  Then Oogrr lifting me into the air, his eyes searching mine, looking for injuries.  I think of the bruise on the back of my head, and giggle.  Life had just gotten a bit more interesting.<BR>
	Night is very cold upon the desert, and Oogrr and I built a small fire to keep us warm.  Well, I say small&#8230;was a small bonfire to me.  Oogrr lying down next to the flames, I duck into the tent and pray to Tunare for rest, uninterrupted.  One night, please.<BR>
Yet, I can feel him pulling, reaching out to my dreams&#8230;trying to summon me back to him.  I see his face dart across my dreams.  Blue eyes, like icicles.  Raven black hair.  Skin the color of midnight.  Mockery and malice dancing in those eyes.  Thrashing about, I find my arms restrained, frightened I lurch awake.  There lies my knight, holding me.  Seeing me wake, he goes to leave and sit by the fire once more.  I stay his arm, begging him with my eyes not to leave me.  Gently, he lies down beside me, and lies his arm down that I can use it as a pillow.  And when sleep came, it was the kind of sleep that one feels when they are a newborn resting on there mother&#8217;s chest.  A rest of safety, and peace.  He could not reach me here; I was safe once more.<BR>
	In the morning, Oogrr taught me more of the land, describing the swamps and lush lands he had hailed from.  He told how He had met Balroger and Summerwynd, and they became friends.  Would seem that my sister was engaged to be married, and had found a home.  My heart bubbly with pride for she was seen as a Northman among her people, and she was worried she was a failure.  I heard word that my cousin Jakkee was safe also in the lands of Antonica.  Life was beginning to smile upon me again. My knight had saved me and brought be back to the land of sanity.  We hunted and laughed together, each day, our friendship growing stronger.  They say that beauty is within the spirit and soul, not the flesh.  I know this to be true.  For why else would I see such beauty in Oogrr.  His kindness, his laughter, then way he would try to cook and then blush when he broke the spit again.  Some tried to ridicule our friendship, but then they would have to deal with me.  And there is nothing to fear more in Norrath then a ranger with an attitude&#8230;that could be lethal to one&#8217;s health.<BR>
	All good things come to an end&#8230;or so I was told.  Oogrr would be leaving me to return to Ferrott.  Asking me to wait for him, heart cried out for him to stay. Pride would stay my tongue, he knew my heart, and yes, I would wait even to the end of time.  And so I stood on the dunes, watching my  dearest friend return to the swamps from whence he came.  The dreams had become bad memories in the arms of my dear Oogrr.  Barely remembering them, or the events that brought me to this man, I knew only the happiness I felt with him.  The sun began to set along the Ocean of Tears, and a wind chilling to the bone seemed to be blowing this eve.  Clutching my cloak tighter, I return to the dune in which Oogrr and I had shared many an afternoon.  Rekindling a smaller version of our bonfires, the flames almost hypnotic in their dance with the wind.  Images of our days together, flitting about in my mind.  The day he gave me a new bow, and the ensuing archery lesson.  The smacking of his arm and the resounding thud,  the dancing about and cursing.  Giggling, trying to get him to get him to hold still so I could see the wound.  The kiss on the cheek afterwards, ahhh, and the laughter.  Reminiscing, I wipe a tear from my eye.  He will return to me soon.<BR>
	The howl of a wolf tells of the passing hours, and I duck into my tent.  Placing my hand upon the pillow on which Oogrr laid his head, Sinking into the oblivion of sleep.  <BR>
	The heady scent of Kelethin assails my senses.  A bitterness of cinnamon and morning dew, intermingling to give the journeyman a sense of alcoholic ease when passing through.  Rustling of leaves brings my vision to my left.  There sits a dressmaker&#8217;s doll, a wine red dress with golden trim rests upon it&#8217;s frame.  Ah, my wedding dress, was I to marry Oogrr in this dream, but why Kelethin, would not my love be murdered here?  A passing shadow draws my gaze to a desk: quills, parchments  and inks line the top.  One parchment is unrolled, signatures scribbled along the bottoms.  Heavy with dread, as though my very being were poisoned with fear, I stand and walk to the desk.  Skimming the document, my eyes grow wider with horror.  There at the bottom, my signature, and that of&#8230;.o dear Tunare&#8230;NO!!<BR>
	Laughter surrounds me, turning in circles, no one is there.  Moving without thought, I reach for the parchment.  I must destroy it if I am to ever know freedom.  The movement alone was astounding, one moment I was reaching for the parchment, the next a hand was bring my head crashing to the desk.  Reeling from the pain, I stagger back &#8230; into the creature.  Grabbing my wrists he pulls my arms up and behind me. I can feel the tendons of my arms screaming, on the verge of ripping.  Eyes clinched in pain, I feel more than see the salty taste of his lips on mine.  The brush of his fingertips across my cheek; the stingy needles as he strikes me.<BR>
 &quot;Did you forget...Dear Child&#8230;you belong to me,&quot; the rancor of his breath on my lips.  &quot;I own you, as if you were my pet or dog.&quot;  Again the stroking of his finger tips along my stingy cheek.<BR>
	Trying to kick out, I loose my footing.  Pain shooting through my arms, I feel the muscles wanting to give.  A reprieve, as my arms drop to my sides.  It has let me go.  My head, light and dizzy from the pain, crashes against the forest&#8217;s lush carpet, smelling the scent of home.  And knowing no safety&#8230;I need to wake.  Every ounce of me screaming to wake from this Hell.  Serpent-like, his fingers slowly intertwine into my hair, pulling my head from the soft earth.  Those callous and cold eyes searching mine.  The hatred, the love, inter-mingling to where one could not tell one from the other.<BR>
	&quot;I grow weary of waiting, my love, &quot; he spits the words into my face. &quot;And now is the time to decide, honour the contract&#8230;NOW.&quot;  Releasing my hair, the ground once more rushes to meet me.  A stone splices my lip and blood begins to slowly trickle down my lips.  Reeling and scared, I look for an escape&#8230;do not all dreams have a way out?<BR>
	Fear clutching my heart, I spat the words, &quot;Love you?  Is that what you want, &quot;trying to buy time to find a way around him and his beast.  &quot; Never saw you as the Feir dal type&#8230;my love.&quot;  The bile rising in my throat as I say those words.  What did this creature know of love, he only knew pain and hate.  &quot;How would you have me honour it, marry and hate you all at once?  Is that what you seek?&quot;<BR>
	Laughter, slow and deliberate&#8230;it&#8217;s intonations sending ice into my heart. His hands were caressing and playing with some instrument, perhaps to scare me. Or perhaps it was the jar of the tortured barbarian.  Please not the jar of that poor man, I could not bear to see that tormented face once more.  His body shifts slightly, letting the moonlight play against the dagger in his hands.  Nimbly, twirling it between is fingertips.  A silvery, moonlit metal that sings in the darkness encasing us.  My haggard visage reflecting back to me&#8230; the fear and hopelessness in my eyes.<BR>
	&quot;Fool child, you do not understand the contract.&quot; With the speed of light, he was on me.  His lips close to mine, but a hair separation.  Shoving the contract before my eyes. &quot;See&#8230;reads till death do us part, and well,&quot; a callous giggle from his lips. He carelessly tosses the parchment aside. &quot; I love another, and I do so like everything to be formal and legal. I&#8217;m sure that your cousin will see logic where you failed.&quot; Again the cold laughter against my ear, his lips tantalizingly close so he had only to whisper.  &quot;For you see, when you left, they chose another.  Now &#8230;I must clear the way for her.&quot;	<BR>
	His lips crush against mine, possessing my mouth once more, and a fierce fire explodes within my chest. It seemed to start there and was burning my insides alive.  Glancing down, I see the dagger had found its sheath.  The blood softly flowing from the wound through my heart. Thoughts reeling through my mind, the taste of blood rising within my throat.  Clutching for air, for release of the pain, I cling to this man, my enemy.  As the life leaves my body, I shed a single tear for the ogre who had possessed my heart, and who would never know.  Destiny and Fate had found me. My fears had found me sleeping, and death came to me in the arms on my teir dal husband.<BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
